  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the reason behind driving on the left hand side and the right hand side of the road in different countries?",
  "response": "The practice of driving on the left or right side of the road has historical roots that date back centuries. The primary reason for these differences lies in the historical practices of different countries and their subsequent influence on traffic regulations.\n\n### Driving on the Left:\n- **Historical Origin**: The tradition of driving on the left side of the road can be traced back to ancient times, particularly to the Roman Empire. Soldiers and travelers would walk on the left side of the road to keep their right hand (the sword hand) free for defense.\n- **Influence of Horse Riding**: In medieval England, the practice continued with horse riders. Since most people are right-handed, it was safer and more practical to mount and dismount horses from the left side, which required staying on the left side of the road.\n- **Napoleonic Influence**: Many countries that drive on the left were once part of the British Empire. Britain maintained its left-side driving rule, and its colonies followed suit.\n\n### Driving on the Right:\n- **Napoleonic Influence**: Napoleon Bonaparte, being left-handed, is said to have preferred that his armies march on the right side of the road. As he conquered much of Europe, he imposed this rule, leading many countries to adopt right-side driving.\n- **Influence of the USA**: After gaining independence, the United States chose to differentiate itself from British customs, including adopting right-side driving. The influence of the USA and its growing economy helped spread this practice to other parts of the Americas and beyond.\n- **Standardization and Safety**: In the 20th century, many countries switched to right-side driving to align with their neighbors and major trade partners, often for reasons of safety and standardization. For instance, Sweden switched from left to right in 1967.\n\n### Current Situation:\nToday, about 75% of the world's countries drive on the right side of the road, while approximately 25% drive on the left. Countries that drive on the left are mostly former British colonies, including the United Kingdom, Australia, New Zealand, India, and several others.\n\nThe choice of which side to drive on has been largely influenced by historical events, colonial ties, and subsequent decisions made by governments to align with neighboring countries or major trade partners for economic and safety reasons.",
